WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.842 --> 00:00:07.800
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
Welcome to Talks at Google.

00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:08.930
I'm Mark de Schweinitz.

00:00:08.930 --> 00:00:10.330
I'm here with Tom McPhee.

00:00:10.330 --> 00:00:11.584
Tom, thanks for joining us.

00:00:11.584 --> 00:00:13.000
TOM MCPHEE: Oh,
my pleasure, Mark.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:15.235
I actually came
bearing gifts, too.

00:00:15.235 --> 00:00:17.917
I know you can't see
it in front of here.

00:00:17.917 --> 00:00:20.250
But I wanted to really thank
you because I do appreciate

00:00:20.250 --> 00:00:23.890
you giving me this opportunity
and just the friendship

00:00:23.890 --> 00:00:25.250
that we've started to develop.

00:00:25.250 --> 00:00:26.270
I appreciate that.

00:00:26.270 --> 00:00:30.139
This is what got me
started in this whole field

00:00:30.139 --> 00:00:30.930
in the first place.

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:33.263
So I want to give you have
copy of my movie "An American

00:00:33.263 --> 00:00:33.806
Opera."

00:00:33.806 --> 00:00:35.264
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
Wow, thank you.

00:00:35.264 --> 00:00:36.080
That's awesome.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:37.538
I'm definitely
going to watch this.

00:00:37.538 --> 00:00:39.766
I'm a big documentary fan,
so I look forward to that.

00:00:39.766 --> 00:00:40.740
TOM MCPHEE: Thanks.

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:41.781
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Good.

00:00:41.781 --> 00:00:44.560
Well, Tom and I first
met about a year ago.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:47.280
It was at a Google
for Nonprofits.

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:48.360
I was a volunteer.

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:50.910
Tom was here in the
office at Ann Arbor.

00:00:50.910 --> 00:00:53.300
And I saw a video
of what he does.

00:00:53.300 --> 00:00:58.840
It was a about himself running
down Gratiot Avenue in Detroit,

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:02.850
documenting dogs and the
problems that some of them

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:06.410
are facing based on abuse
and other problems like that.

00:01:06.410 --> 00:01:08.210
I was impressed by
what you did, Tom.

00:01:08.210 --> 00:01:09.484
So thanks for coming.

00:01:09.484 --> 00:01:10.650
TOM MCPHEE: Oh, my pleasure.

00:01:10.650 --> 00:01:13.185
And I can't believe
it's been, seriously,

00:01:13.185 --> 00:01:15.050
a year since that took place.

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:17.134
Was it really last
fall, last late fall?

00:01:17.134 --> 00:01:19.050
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Yeah,
something like that.

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:20.550
TOM MCPHEE: Oh, my goodness.

00:01:20.550 --> 00:01:20.810
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Yeah.

00:01:20.810 --> 00:01:22.990
And what we really want
to learn about today

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:28.220
is what you do as a filmmaker,
making documentaries like this,

00:01:28.220 --> 00:01:30.050
and how we can learn
as Googlers and others

00:01:30.050 --> 00:01:33.689
watching how to tell great
stories through video,

00:01:33.689 --> 00:01:34.730
and other ways like that.

00:01:34.730 --> 00:01:36.340
So first, maybe you
could just tell us

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:39.630
what you do in general as
a documentary filmmaker?

00:01:39.630 --> 00:01:41.450
TOM MCPHEE: Well,
I'm kind of, I think,

00:01:41.450 --> 00:01:42.892
a very contemporary hybrid.

00:01:42.892 --> 00:01:46.770
I've been fancying about
the whole independent film

00:01:46.770 --> 00:01:49.120
scene for a long time.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:54.090
I actually started my
career in technology.

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:57.370
I worked for Hamilton Avnet
and then Avnet Computer.

00:01:57.370 --> 00:01:59.622
And I [INAUDIBLE]
big-box computers

00:01:59.622 --> 00:02:02.920
coupled with really
expensive software.

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:06.332
That afforded me to get involved
with creating my own software

00:02:06.332 --> 00:02:08.956
company in the early '90s.

00:02:08.956 --> 00:02:14.600
And the whole reason for me was
to get closer to film-making.

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:17.895
And initially, for many
years, that process

00:02:17.895 --> 00:02:23.390
was making interactive content
for commercial entities

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:27.560
like Ford and Saturn and
so on here in a car town.

00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:29.120
But I always wanted
to be involved

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:32.098
with the more commercial
or the more available

00:02:32.098 --> 00:02:34.462
form of entertainment.

00:02:34.462 --> 00:02:37.511
And I like documentaries
a lot, too.

00:02:37.511 --> 00:02:40.614
But I was able to make
some independent films.

00:02:40.614 --> 00:02:42.670
I was able to create
an independent film

00:02:42.670 --> 00:02:46.770
tour called Flicks Tour that
toured around the country.

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:51.640
We actually helped, in
essence, find Paul Feig.

00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:54.714
Paul Feig, who now just got
"Ghostbusters" that's coming

00:02:54.714 --> 00:02:56.490
out, he did "Bridesmaids."

00:02:56.490 --> 00:03:00.370
He did "Spy."

00:03:00.370 --> 00:03:02.962
His coming out was
"Freaks and Geeks."

00:03:02.962 --> 00:03:05.830
And he wrote that while he was
on my film tour, the Flicks

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:07.725
Tour, at that time.

00:03:07.725 --> 00:03:11.500
And Kevin Smith actually
started doing his college

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:16.340
touring because he appeared at
a couple of our presentations

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:18.295
with Flicks Tour on
the college circuit.

00:03:18.295 --> 00:03:20.900
And we were always
mobbed when he was there.

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:24.542
Now he's making, like, $50,000
and up per three hours.

00:03:24.542 --> 00:03:26.000
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
That'd be nice.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:26.958
TOM MCPHEE: Oh, I know.

00:03:26.958 --> 00:03:27.470
It's crazy.

00:03:27.470 --> 00:03:29.810
But for me, I was
really fascinated

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:35.280
with telling stories and
being able to communicate.

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:38.540
I always thought I was going
to be a baseball player.

00:03:38.540 --> 00:03:42.330
Since I couldn't be a baseball
player forever, what do you do?

00:03:42.330 --> 00:03:47.510
And as a storyteller, I can
tell stories all my life.

00:03:47.510 --> 00:03:49.510
You know, the rest of my life.

00:03:49.510 --> 00:03:52.680
In this realm, though, I'm
telling stories visually.

00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:56.470
It has been a 25-year
journey for me

00:03:56.470 --> 00:04:00.000
to go from producer hiring
people and interacting

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.293
with people to make movies.

00:04:01.293 --> 00:04:05.560
The very first movie I made
was with Bruce Campbell.

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:07.010
It was a little
independent film.

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:09.070
I don't know if people
know horror films.

00:04:09.070 --> 00:04:12.470
And we just lost Gunnar Hansen,
who was the original "Texas

00:04:12.470 --> 00:04:14.440
Chainsaw Massacre" leatherface.

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:16.866
But he was our
star in our movie.

00:04:16.866 --> 00:04:18.931
When you're doing
a horror film, you

00:04:18.931 --> 00:04:21.019
need to have some kind of icon.

00:04:21.019 --> 00:04:23.050
But Gunnar just passed away.

00:04:23.050 --> 00:04:24.260
Rest his soul.

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:29.790
But I went from that
to going through a book

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:32.330
should gyrations of
trying to understand what

00:04:32.330 --> 00:04:34.590
I wanted to do in this realm.

00:04:34.590 --> 00:04:40.820
And in 2005, as soon as
Hurricane Katrina hit

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:42.940
and everything took
place there, I'd

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:45.954
been doing this type of
stuff for 15, 20 years.

00:04:45.954 --> 00:04:48.972
And I found myself being in--

00:04:48.972 --> 00:04:50.180
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: This one?

00:04:50.180 --> 00:04:53.015
TOM MCPHEE: That's right
--in New Orleans immediately

00:04:53.015 --> 00:04:53.515
afterwards.

00:04:53.515 --> 00:04:55.378
We thought we were
going to help people.

00:04:55.378 --> 00:04:59.150
And a very specific moment
in time sort of flashed.

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:00.974
It literally just happened.

00:05:00.974 --> 00:05:04.890
And I saw the next three to
five years in front of me.

00:05:04.890 --> 00:05:09.050
And that was-- I
thought I was seeing

00:05:09.050 --> 00:05:13.790
our evolutionary
essence, how we evolve.

00:05:13.790 --> 00:05:18.060
In front my eyes, in this
catastrophic environment,

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:20.510
people were trying to do good.

00:05:20.510 --> 00:05:23.130
So you had a bunch of people
trying to do good with people.

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:25.670
But then you had
this mass of humanity

00:05:25.670 --> 00:05:29.100
that came down to try to
do good with animals, too.

00:05:29.100 --> 00:05:33.190
And when I started to look at
how this whole thing played

00:05:33.190 --> 00:05:38.710
out, I thought, this is
amazing because the facade

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:41.430
of everything and what
we are was ripped away.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:45.190
And you could actually
see people's essence

00:05:45.190 --> 00:05:46.561
in their humanity.

00:05:46.561 --> 00:05:49.620
And I thought it was
the perfect opportunity

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:54.530
to figure out a way to
spend time with this realm,

00:05:54.530 --> 00:05:59.135
to tell stories, and, for
me, uncover our evolution

00:05:59.135 --> 00:06:06.150
in real time-- not in the
future looking back at us,

00:06:06.150 --> 00:06:06.857
but right now.

00:06:06.857 --> 00:06:07.440
What do we do?

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:09.689
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: So this
film, "An American Opera,"

00:06:09.689 --> 00:06:14.273
is about people saving their
pets after Hurricane Katrina?

00:06:14.273 --> 00:06:15.160
Is that correct?

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:19.330
TOM MCPHEE: Well, actually,
it's about the disaster

00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:20.900
within a disaster.

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:25.410
And what happened was in this
disaster, about three days,

00:06:25.410 --> 00:06:28.155
four days into it, there
was a fourth evacuation

00:06:28.155 --> 00:06:31.370
because people hadn't left for
a lot of different reasons.

00:06:31.370 --> 00:06:34.010
And many of those
people, a huge portion

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:37.980
of the population, because
they can't take their pets.

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:41.490
And so when they were
forced to evacuate,

00:06:41.490 --> 00:06:44.876
they were forcibly
separated from their pets.

00:06:44.876 --> 00:06:46.625
And there were literally
tens of thousands

00:06:46.625 --> 00:06:49.485
of animals of all
sorts left behind.

00:06:49.485 --> 00:06:52.456
And there was all kinds
of really horrific things

00:06:52.456 --> 00:06:53.330
happening there, too.

00:06:53.330 --> 00:06:55.580
I know we've heard
about the situation

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:57.930
with the people being
gunned down on the bridge.

00:06:57.930 --> 00:07:01.030
But in St. Bernard Parish,
for two whole days,

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:03.920
the police were going
up and down the streets

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:05.402
shooting everybody's dogs.

00:07:05.402 --> 00:07:09.540
They actually sent out
texts to their fellow--

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:11.949
because in those
situations, firemen,

00:07:11.949 --> 00:07:13.740
police around the world
help band together,

00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:14.690
hey, what do you need?

00:07:14.690 --> 00:07:17.120
And there's texts of
the police going, hey,

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:18.144
we need more bullets.

00:07:18.144 --> 00:07:20.602
We ran out of bullets shooting
all the dogs in the streets.

00:07:20.602 --> 00:07:21.180
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
Oh, that's terrible.

00:07:21.180 --> 00:07:24.280
TOM MCPHEE: And it's a story
that people don't really

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:24.780
realize.

00:07:27.327 --> 00:07:28.160
And I didn't either.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:30.754
And this is the
thing that kind of

00:07:30.754 --> 00:07:34.730
cauterized this or kind
of made this real for me.

00:07:34.730 --> 00:07:39.280
And that is the fact that there
is this soul-bond connection

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:40.770
with people, with animals.

00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:42.239
They're family members.

00:07:42.239 --> 00:07:47.020
And you can't just-- so you
things go wrong at that point

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:51.462
when you try to
separate families.

00:07:51.462 --> 00:07:54.100
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: So when
you went down to Louisiana

00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:55.480
after this disaster,
did you know

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:57.595
that you'd be
making a documentary

00:07:57.595 --> 00:07:58.800
about this incident?

00:07:58.800 --> 00:07:58.940
TOM MCPHEE: No.

00:07:58.940 --> 00:08:00.030
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Or you
just went down and said,

00:08:00.030 --> 00:08:01.595
this is something
terrible happening.

00:08:01.595 --> 00:08:03.470
I need to figure out
how I can help here?

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:07.960
TOM MCPHEE: We heard Mayor Nagin
basically pleading for help

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:14.790
on that September 1, like a
couple days after the storm.

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:17.170
And he was pleading
for assistance,

00:08:17.170 --> 00:08:19.630
in essence crying on the radio.

00:08:19.630 --> 00:08:21.460
And I heard this a
couple days later

00:08:21.460 --> 00:08:23.300
when I was getting ready
for something else.

00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:26.830
And I just felt like I
have to do something.

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:29.620
I'm at a moment in time
I can go address this.

00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:31.360
I'm going to go down there.

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:33.966
We thought we were going
to be helping pull people,

00:08:33.966 --> 00:08:37.299
dead bodies out of
the-- I had no concept

00:08:37.299 --> 00:08:39.767
about animal-related--
oh, this is a new world.

00:08:39.767 --> 00:08:41.767
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: So
this was, really, a foray

00:08:41.767 --> 00:08:43.510
into animal-related film?

00:08:43.510 --> 00:08:44.820
TOM MCPHEE: Absolutely.

00:08:44.820 --> 00:08:46.250
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: And
this was about 10 years ago?

00:08:46.250 --> 00:08:46.873
TOM MCPHEE: Yes.

00:08:46.873 --> 00:08:47.831
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: OK.

00:08:47.831 --> 00:08:49.980
TOM MCPHEE: When it
happened, when I went down,

00:08:49.980 --> 00:08:52.355
it was early September, 2005.

00:08:52.355 --> 00:08:56.180
And I had been doing this
type of production, producer,

00:08:56.180 --> 00:08:57.226
and so on.

00:08:57.226 --> 00:09:00.450
But I ended up participating
on two Animal Planet

00:09:00.450 --> 00:09:03.216
specials about the event,
a National Geographic

00:09:03.216 --> 00:09:12.885
special, and Nova, their
natural history series.

00:09:12.885 --> 00:09:15.980
It was on there, too.

00:09:15.980 --> 00:09:19.190
And they were looking at
certain aspects of the story.

00:09:19.190 --> 00:09:21.600
And I was seeing a much
richer story down there.

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:23.350
And so I wanted to
tell the greater story.

00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:26.202
And that's why the
movie came out of it,

00:09:26.202 --> 00:09:27.910
because there was
quite a bit of material

00:09:27.910 --> 00:09:30.460
that I participated in.

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:35.380
I needed to tell my story, what
I saw, this ongoing situation.

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:38.100
Once all the dogs, in
essence, or animals,

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:41.386
were scattered about, as
people were fostering them

00:09:41.386 --> 00:09:46.410
around the country, and then
people were working behind

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:48.387
the scenes around
the country going,

00:09:48.387 --> 00:09:50.220
oh, I couldn't have
been there, but maybe we

00:09:50.220 --> 00:09:52.790
can help reunite
animals, then you

00:09:52.790 --> 00:09:56.670
had this mass of people
trying to find these dogs.

00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:59.630
And so our photographs,
about 10,000

00:09:59.630 --> 00:10:03.210
of them that we shot immediately
when we got down there

00:10:03.210 --> 00:10:07.220
were used to start to put all
the people and animals back

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:08.330
together.

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:10.431
And then you had a
whole other disaster

00:10:10.431 --> 00:10:11.972
because the people
who were fostering

00:10:11.972 --> 00:10:14.472
didn't want to give
the animals back.

00:10:14.472 --> 00:10:17.480
They go, oh, these people
left those animals.

00:10:17.480 --> 00:10:19.624
They shouldn't have them.

00:10:19.624 --> 00:10:20.790
So there was so many things.

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:23.310
There were so many layers going
onto this, and the humanity.

00:10:23.310 --> 00:10:31.250
And again, it created a whole
bunch of content for history.

00:10:31.250 --> 00:10:34.490
"An American Opera" and all
of its contents, by the way,

00:10:34.490 --> 00:10:37.980
is going into the
Library of Congress.

00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:41.880
And it was a very
important period of time.

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:44.838
The animal welfare and
animal rescue realm

00:10:44.838 --> 00:10:46.380
really blew up at that point.

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:50.430
There's two contributing
factors-- social media,

00:10:50.430 --> 00:10:54.290
because Facebook, Craig's
List was a huge impact

00:10:54.290 --> 00:10:55.820
on that environment.

00:10:55.820 --> 00:10:59.620
And then this event,
this massive event

00:10:59.620 --> 00:11:02.200
that people saw unfold
on their-- they had

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:06.148
seen five years before-- 9/11.

00:11:06.148 --> 00:11:07.680
Oh, my god.

00:11:07.680 --> 00:11:09.650
What do you do
after-- and here, they

00:11:09.650 --> 00:11:13.180
watched this event unfold
over a couple days.

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:16.360
And they go, that's close
enough that I can drive there.

00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:19.610
Even if they're somewhere in
Quebec or Washington state,

00:11:19.610 --> 00:11:21.990
people were driving
there to help out,

00:11:21.990 --> 00:11:23.145
and tens of thousands.

00:11:23.145 --> 00:11:28.360
And I was part of
that collective

00:11:28.360 --> 00:11:32.397
that was down there that
had those experiences

00:11:32.397 --> 00:11:34.355
and then had those
experiences for many months.

00:11:34.355 --> 00:11:36.790
Then I interacted with
a lot of those people

00:11:36.790 --> 00:11:40.470
again to watch their evolution.

00:11:40.470 --> 00:11:42.270
And it's been amazing.

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:44.791
Just this year, they had
the 10-year anniversary.

00:11:44.791 --> 00:11:47.040
And again, there were 10-year
anniversary [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:47.040 --> 00:11:49.520
I was filming something else,
so I couldn't go this year,

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:52.412
but I filmed a bunch of
five-year reunion stuff.

00:11:52.412 --> 00:11:53.120
I was down there.

00:11:53.120 --> 00:11:55.317
I was actually down
there at that time

00:11:55.317 --> 00:12:00.500
covering the BP disaster
in the Gulf for WA2S Films.

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:03.175
So that's what kind of
initiated everything.

00:12:03.175 --> 00:12:05.250
And then a publisher
friend of mine

00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:09.607
said, hey, we really want to
get behind what you're doing.

00:12:09.607 --> 00:12:11.190
And we think we can
get behind it more

00:12:11.190 --> 00:12:13.032
if you started a nonprofit.

00:12:13.032 --> 00:12:15.177
And I thought about that.

00:12:15.177 --> 00:12:16.635
And I said, aw,
that's a good idea.

00:12:16.635 --> 00:12:18.801
I'd love to just because I
don't want to go and fund

00:12:18.801 --> 00:12:20.230
each individual thing.

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:23.320
We need to be able to figure
out how to create an entity

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:24.677
to fund all the things.

00:12:24.677 --> 00:12:26.260
I want to be able
to be in a situation

00:12:26.260 --> 00:12:30.610
where our organization
can, at six hours notice

00:12:30.610 --> 00:12:33.780
after a major disaster,
go off into that disaster.

00:12:33.780 --> 00:12:34.730
I was at BP.

00:12:34.730 --> 00:12:35.900
We were in Fukushima.

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:39.150
We were in Haiti studying
the relationships and stuff.

00:12:41.447 --> 00:12:43.155
This publisher friend
of mine said, look,

00:12:43.155 --> 00:12:45.050
you need to do this.

00:12:45.050 --> 00:12:46.994
And I thought about it.

00:12:46.994 --> 00:12:48.600
I said, OK.

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:50.500
And then I told her the name.

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:52.610
She was like, what's that?

00:12:52.610 --> 00:12:53.830
Like, because it's so long.

00:12:53.830 --> 00:12:55.680
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: The World
Animal Awareness Society?

00:12:55.680 --> 00:12:57.850
TOM MCPHEE: Yeah, it's a
mouthful and a half, right?

00:12:57.850 --> 00:13:01.936
She was like, why don't you
just call it, like, Dogville?

00:13:01.936 --> 00:13:02.770
It's like, well, no.

00:13:02.770 --> 00:13:04.602
I want it to do something
a little bit more.

00:13:04.602 --> 00:13:06.545
We don't want to do just
funny animal things.

00:13:06.545 --> 00:13:09.042
We want to do stuff that's
really meaningful here.

00:13:09.042 --> 00:13:10.583
And unfortunately,
I want to pack all

00:13:10.583 --> 00:13:12.882
of what we do into that name.

00:13:12.882 --> 00:13:15.507
So, World Animal
Awareness Society,

00:13:15.507 --> 00:13:18.312
which says exactly what we are.

00:13:18.312 --> 00:13:20.770
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: And what's
the goal of the World Animal

00:13:20.770 --> 00:13:21.700
Awareness Society?

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:23.370
TOM MCPHEE: To be
able to tell stories

00:13:23.370 --> 00:13:26.510
that [INAUDIBLE] human-animal
interaction to try

00:13:26.510 --> 00:13:29.050
to understand our
evolutionary arc.

00:13:29.050 --> 00:13:32.390
I mean, it really boils down
to that simple of a thing.

00:13:32.390 --> 00:13:38.330
And our URL, which is an homage
to Ann Arbor, too, is wa2s.org.

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:42.170
Anybody who knows Ann Arbor
knows it's A2 or A-squared.

00:13:42.170 --> 00:13:45.986
Our A-squared is
Animal Awareness.

00:13:45.986 --> 00:13:47.430
So it's wa2s.org.

00:13:49.397 --> 00:13:50.480
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Great.

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:53.730
So before we learn
more about wa2s.org,

00:13:53.730 --> 00:13:57.230
can you share with us how you
develop a story, such as when

00:13:57.230 --> 00:13:59.310
you made "An American Opera"?

00:13:59.310 --> 00:14:02.530
What was your
process for saying,

00:14:02.530 --> 00:14:05.020
in a 45-minute, an
hour-long documentary,

00:14:05.020 --> 00:14:07.770
here is the
start-to-finish of a story?

00:14:07.770 --> 00:14:10.670
Just more for education
for our viewers,

00:14:10.670 --> 00:14:12.130
how do you tell a
story like that?

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:14.200
TOM MCPHEE: I appreciate that.

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:15.880
I've been doing this
a long time now.

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:18.470
I'm starting to figure out
all the different processes

00:14:18.470 --> 00:14:20.520
and how to use what I'm doing.

00:14:20.520 --> 00:14:22.785
And you asked me early on
about being a filmmaker.

00:14:22.785 --> 00:14:24.785
I think I'm a contemporary
filmmaker because I'm

00:14:24.785 --> 00:14:26.380
making for the internet.

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:28.140
I making for commercial.

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:30.930
I'm making for
television, theatrical.

00:14:30.930 --> 00:14:32.690
And so they're all different.

00:14:32.690 --> 00:14:37.280
But they all kind of
contribute to each other.

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:40.140
A lot of filmmakers don't really
understand that, by the way.

00:14:40.140 --> 00:14:47.760
I love, love, love YouTube,
Google, the Google family.

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:52.010
It's been a great partnership
with Google Nonprofit.

00:14:52.010 --> 00:14:54.930
And YouTube is just
such a powerful entity

00:14:54.930 --> 00:14:56.890
to be able to create
my own channel

00:14:56.890 --> 00:15:00.630
and be able to communicate
what's going on in the world.

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:04.601
It's been truly phenomenal.

00:15:04.601 --> 00:15:09.000
But for me, there has
been this evolution.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.110
And I think it starts
with understanding,

00:15:12.110 --> 00:15:13.710
where's your target?

00:15:13.710 --> 00:15:15.630
And then, what's your medium?

00:15:15.630 --> 00:15:20.249
And so that whole idea of,
are we really targeting

00:15:20.249 --> 00:15:20.790
the internet?

00:15:20.790 --> 00:15:24.952
Are we targeting--
"The Martian" looks

00:15:24.952 --> 00:15:27.660
very different than
"An American Opera."

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:30.602
There's a whole different thing
in terms of cost and everything

00:15:30.602 --> 00:15:32.200
that goes into it.

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:36.160
And so for me, as a
documentary filmmaker,

00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:39.050
I don't want to
create the construct.

00:15:39.050 --> 00:15:41.190
I want you observe the world.

00:15:41.190 --> 00:15:44.820
And then I want to assemble
based on what I've seen

00:15:44.820 --> 00:15:47.910
and what I've assimilated
of that information.

00:15:47.910 --> 00:15:50.430
"An American Opera," I was
just talking about this

00:15:50.430 --> 00:15:53.836
with somebody recently ago.

00:15:53.836 --> 00:15:58.465
When do you get into being able
to talk about facts and figures

00:15:58.465 --> 00:15:59.860
with a documentary?

00:15:59.860 --> 00:16:03.050
When is it a good
situation to look

00:16:03.050 --> 00:16:06.060
at maybe the emotional
aspects of the storytelling?

00:16:06.060 --> 00:16:09.640
And for "An American Opera,"
because the facts weren't

00:16:09.640 --> 00:16:12.480
known, it was such
a big crazy mess

00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:16.060
that you couldn't really sort
through what was going on.

00:16:16.060 --> 00:16:19.270
And the emotions
took huge precedence.

00:16:19.270 --> 00:16:23.846
The idea was here we just
happened to be at ground zero

00:16:23.846 --> 00:16:24.970
when those things happened.

00:16:24.970 --> 00:16:26.910
And you start to kind
of work your way out.

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:28.310
OK, where are the story threads?

00:16:28.310 --> 00:16:28.977
What's going on?

00:16:28.977 --> 00:16:30.851
That's when we found
that the dogs were being

00:16:30.851 --> 00:16:32.480
murdered in St. Bernard Parish.

00:16:32.480 --> 00:16:35.190
That's when we find that
people are [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:35.190 --> 00:16:39.740
That's when we go chase
after Marilyn Pickens,

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:42.490
[INAUDIBLE] Pickens'
wife, was flying dogs out

00:16:42.490 --> 00:16:46.360
by the Airbus load.

00:16:46.360 --> 00:16:49.196
So we went down to the
airport, and we're filming.

00:16:49.196 --> 00:16:52.940
You go, oh, there's
something going on here.

00:16:52.940 --> 00:16:56.070
And you start to
kind of expand out.

00:16:56.070 --> 00:16:58.590
So that's how
"American Opera" went.

00:16:58.590 --> 00:17:00.380
When I look at
doing doc projects,

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:05.460
though, I want to
take that process.

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:08.109
And the reason is
because every time

00:17:08.109 --> 00:17:11.640
that I started to go and
examine these things,

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:14.569
my brain starts to tell me,
oh, this is what I'm seeing.

00:17:14.569 --> 00:17:15.569
This is what I'm seeing.

00:17:15.569 --> 00:17:16.535
This is kind of
what I'm looking at.

00:17:16.535 --> 00:17:19.470
And as I look at it more, it's
like, oh, no, no, no, no, no.

00:17:19.470 --> 00:17:20.829
There's something else going on.

00:17:20.829 --> 00:17:24.170
There's another layer that
we've got to peel back.

00:17:24.170 --> 00:17:28.200
And time-- and I
appreciate doing long form,

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:31.510
but I'm started to
specialize in short form,

00:17:31.510 --> 00:17:32.570
too, for the internet.

00:17:32.570 --> 00:17:34.690
We shot something
yesterday afternoon.

00:17:34.690 --> 00:17:36.505
It's on the top
of our page right

00:17:36.505 --> 00:17:40.570
now-- wa2s.org-- a bunch of
puppies and dogs being rescued.

00:17:40.570 --> 00:17:41.930
It's a five-minute piece.

00:17:41.930 --> 00:17:43.370
We flipped it around.

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:47.620
We're trying to understand
how to best do look and feel

00:17:47.620 --> 00:17:51.400
and aesthetic and tell a
story and connect with that.

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:53.760
And for us, it also
helps boil down

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:56.112
what might work in a
television piece, what might

00:17:56.112 --> 00:17:58.390
work in a film festival piece.

00:17:58.390 --> 00:18:01.770
And they're different.

00:18:01.770 --> 00:18:05.880
So I've started to look
at how can we just shoot

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:09.560
as much as we can, and
then start to chase

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:10.790
after the different threads.

00:18:10.790 --> 00:18:13.520
And the ones that stick to each
other, you put them together.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:15.020
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
So your approach

00:18:15.020 --> 00:18:16.485
is really go gather the--

00:18:16.485 --> 00:18:17.360
TOM MCPHEE: Oh, yeah.

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:18.220
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
--information,

00:18:18.220 --> 00:18:20.000
just see what's
happening, and then

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.894
figure out what's the
story here as opposed

00:18:22.894 --> 00:18:26.042
to coming in with a
pre-determined plan, structure.

00:18:26.042 --> 00:18:27.500
TOM MCPHEE: One of
the first things

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:30.110
that we did with
World Animal Awareness

00:18:30.110 --> 00:18:36.300
Society was make a presentation
to Rotary in Saline, Michigan.

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:40.390
And I exclaimed what--
and people can you

00:18:40.390 --> 00:18:42.580
find it on our YouTube channel.

00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:45.570
There's a three-part thing
about why we're doing it.

00:18:45.570 --> 00:18:47.735
And for me, it's
about documentum.

00:18:47.735 --> 00:18:49.610
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
Documentum, what is that?

00:18:49.610 --> 00:18:52.600
TOM MCPHEE: It's kind
of the Latin from where

00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:54.510
"documentary" comes
from. "Documentary"

00:18:54.510 --> 00:18:58.830
is a very contemporary word,
like maybe 100 years old or so.

00:19:01.455 --> 00:19:04.770
And it's really come forth
with the moving image.

00:19:04.770 --> 00:19:08.162
But going back 2,000 years or
more, the idea of a documentum

00:19:08.162 --> 00:19:15.150
is telling stories in essence to
learn from, stories to educate,

00:19:15.150 --> 00:19:20.320
to pass on knowledge to
allow you to move forward,

00:19:20.320 --> 00:19:21.960
progressively, happily.

00:19:21.960 --> 00:19:27.736
There's idea of documentum,
just saying what happens.

00:19:27.736 --> 00:19:29.452
And a lot of times,
with documentaries,

00:19:29.452 --> 00:19:34.070
especially now, we're
trying to confect too much.

00:19:34.070 --> 00:19:36.600
And my belief is, and
the whole reason I

00:19:36.600 --> 00:19:39.970
started this was to try to cut
through all of that stuff, all

00:19:39.970 --> 00:19:43.100
the static, to figure
out what's real,

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:47.705
what is really going on here
and not what they're selling me

00:19:47.705 --> 00:19:49.246
or not what this
place is selling me.

00:19:49.246 --> 00:19:51.534
I want to know really
what the deal is.

00:19:51.534 --> 00:19:53.450
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Is
this a belief you have?

00:19:53.450 --> 00:19:57.140
Or is it shared amongst
all of the main documentary

00:19:57.140 --> 00:19:57.740
filmmakers?

00:19:57.740 --> 00:20:00.383
When you go to a Sundance
Film Festival or something

00:20:00.383 --> 00:20:03.755
like that, do you share
this belief with others?

00:20:03.755 --> 00:20:06.150
TOM MCPHEE: I think it all
depends on-- sometimes,

00:20:06.150 --> 00:20:08.660
but I think it all depends
on how successful you are.

00:20:08.660 --> 00:20:12.970
I love watching all
different-- and looking

00:20:12.970 --> 00:20:15.100
at all different-- types
of documentary filmmakers

00:20:15.100 --> 00:20:16.680
for all different
types of reasons.

00:20:16.680 --> 00:20:20.516
I like Michael Moore just for
how commercially successful

00:20:20.516 --> 00:20:22.290
that guy is.

00:20:22.290 --> 00:20:22.966
Amazing.

00:20:22.966 --> 00:20:25.550
Now some of his work has
been really phenomenal, too,

00:20:25.550 --> 00:20:27.362
in terms of how he's
digging up stuff.

00:20:27.362 --> 00:20:29.980
But that's a certain
type of documentary.

00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:32.982
Then you've got Alex Gibney,
who's won some Oscars.

00:20:32.982 --> 00:20:35.680
And he's got a very
specific look to him.

00:20:35.680 --> 00:20:38.880
Morgan Spurlock's got a look.

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:40.610
I've got a lot of
people that I'm

00:20:40.610 --> 00:20:43.715
interacting with in the
filmmaking community.

00:20:43.715 --> 00:20:48.310
And they all kind of-- hey, some
focus in rock documentaries,

00:20:48.310 --> 00:20:50.460
so it kind of has that flavor.

00:20:50.460 --> 00:20:52.920
But everything is evolving
because right now the tools

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:54.738
are evolving.

00:20:54.738 --> 00:21:00.752
We're not working with-- the
fact that I can be-- sorry,

00:21:00.752 --> 00:21:06.450
but I'm killing my mic, too--
an opposite brain person

00:21:06.450 --> 00:21:08.640
coming from the
sales side of things,

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:11.845
to be able to now
really kind of fully

00:21:11.845 --> 00:21:13.925
make the adjustment to
be a creative person

00:21:13.925 --> 00:21:19.570
is because the tools exist--
the digital tools, the cameras.

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:22.772
I'm going to bring this up now
so I don't forget about it.

00:21:22.772 --> 00:21:24.820
I wanted to have some
of our filmmaking

00:21:24.820 --> 00:21:29.010
have a much more
dynamic look to it.

00:21:29.010 --> 00:21:30.622
And so we're using drones.

00:21:30.622 --> 00:21:32.080
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
That's awesome.

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:34.810
TOM MCPHEE: This is
DJI's Inspire 1. ?

00:21:34.810 --> 00:21:36.561
It's super easy to use.

00:21:36.561 --> 00:21:37.894
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Easy to fly?

00:21:37.894 --> 00:21:38.858
No accidents?

00:21:38.858 --> 00:21:39.755
Crashing here?

00:21:39.755 --> 00:21:45.160
TOM MCPHEE: Well, this is the
second one. [LAUGHTER] However,

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:46.220
they are super easy.

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:48.051
It's five minutes
out of the box.

00:21:48.051 --> 00:21:49.780
They've got lots
of stuff built in.

00:21:49.780 --> 00:21:51.610
And their firmware
keeps getting better

00:21:51.610 --> 00:21:53.015
in terms of being able to do it.

00:21:53.015 --> 00:21:54.140
It's got follow technology.

00:21:54.140 --> 00:21:57.510
Now you can actually lock in
wave points and you can focus.

00:21:57.510 --> 00:21:59.530
They have a new
camera system, too.

00:21:59.530 --> 00:22:03.310
But for a filmmaker that's
always been pedestrian

00:22:03.310 --> 00:22:07.270
and on the ground, and wanting
to get into lots of places--

00:22:07.270 --> 00:22:10.000
especially since we've started
the "American Strays" project,

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:10.830
we're chasing dogs.

00:22:10.830 --> 00:22:12.920
We're trying to get into areas
that we just can't get into.

00:22:12.920 --> 00:22:14.180
You want something like this.

00:22:14.180 --> 00:22:16.800
But prior to this,
this past year,

00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:21.755
the technology was too hard to
do in a run-and-done fashion

00:22:21.755 --> 00:22:23.970
like we do it here.

00:22:23.970 --> 00:22:25.010
I throw open the truck.

00:22:25.010 --> 00:22:26.070
I pull it out.

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:27.970
If I had it already
pre-configured,

00:22:27.970 --> 00:22:31.850
all I do is set my compass, kind
of like I do this little dance.

00:22:31.850 --> 00:22:32.441
And I watch.

00:22:32.441 --> 00:22:32.940
I get a GPS.

00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:34.080
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
So I guess it's really

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:35.360
a game changer for you?

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:36.277
TOM MCPHEE: It's huge.

00:22:36.277 --> 00:22:38.110
And it pokes into a lot
of different places.

00:22:38.110 --> 00:22:40.970
We've been able to chase
and find dogs this way

00:22:40.970 --> 00:22:43.330
as part of the work
that we're doing.

00:22:43.330 --> 00:22:46.390
But it also gives us really
dynamic picture-making

00:22:46.390 --> 00:22:47.360
capabilities, too.

00:22:49.950 --> 00:22:52.510
So, yeah, it's
totally game-changing.

00:22:52.510 --> 00:22:54.750
But the thing is, everybody
and their brother's

00:22:54.750 --> 00:22:56.630
going to have one.

00:22:56.630 --> 00:22:59.630
And they are already
starting to have them.

00:22:59.630 --> 00:23:01.727
And you're going to
see them everywhere.

00:23:01.727 --> 00:23:03.560
But then there's going
to be something else.

00:23:03.560 --> 00:23:07.580
And for us, that something
else right now, that is,

00:23:07.580 --> 00:23:11.890
we're doing this series with
teen girls that involves

00:23:11.890 --> 00:23:13.714
animal rescue and technology.

00:23:13.714 --> 00:23:18.440
And we want to use
the Ricoh Theta 360S.

00:23:18.440 --> 00:23:20.200
And we want to attach
it to the girls.

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:20.760
It's a 360.

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:25.780
It's your Google Earth-- your
Google Street camera-- brought

00:23:25.780 --> 00:23:30.430
down into miniature size that
you can attach to somebody.

00:23:30.430 --> 00:23:32.730
360 is the thing, right now.

00:23:32.730 --> 00:23:35.760
And YouTube allows
us to share 360 video

00:23:35.760 --> 00:23:37.140
and to interact with stuff.

00:23:37.140 --> 00:23:38.340
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: So
they wear it on a helmet?

00:23:38.340 --> 00:23:39.090
Or how does this work?

00:23:39.090 --> 00:23:40.910
TOM MCPHEE: Yeah, we'll
probably figure out the best way

00:23:40.910 --> 00:23:41.760
to wear it.

00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:43.484
It might on a chestie.

00:23:43.484 --> 00:23:44.460
It might be a helmet.

00:23:44.460 --> 00:23:46.140
But we'll figure that out.

00:23:46.140 --> 00:23:48.230
My guess is it would
probably be up front.

00:23:48.230 --> 00:23:50.250
That way the person
is in the action.

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:52.300
But then the person
looking at them is here.

00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:57.310
So we'll film conventionally
certain parts of the series.

00:23:57.310 --> 00:24:00.010
But then you can
go online and have

00:24:00.010 --> 00:24:02.026
this more immersive experience.

00:24:02.026 --> 00:24:05.665
Especially if you're a girl
to-- you work with this material

00:24:05.665 --> 00:24:08.530
that these other girls
are doing by being

00:24:08.530 --> 00:24:10.660
able to explore in the video.

00:24:10.660 --> 00:24:12.420
It's accessible right now.

00:24:12.420 --> 00:24:14.550
As a matter of fact,
we're looking for donors.

00:24:14.550 --> 00:24:17.270
We're trying to raise--
get four cameras.

00:24:17.270 --> 00:24:22.885
They're like $350 a piece
to get the 360 HD video.

00:24:22.885 --> 00:24:23.763
It's crazy.

00:24:23.763 --> 00:24:26.822
Technology's very,
very available.

00:24:26.822 --> 00:24:28.280
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
So, Tom, you've

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:31.866
mentioned the evolution
of more traditional media,

00:24:31.866 --> 00:24:35.360
television to
YouTube, the internet.

00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:38.880
How have you
changed your content

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:40.410
or the way you do
your work because

00:24:40.410 --> 00:24:42.440
of YouTube and the internet?

00:24:42.440 --> 00:24:44.680
TOM MCPHEE: I'm a
[INAUDIBLE] genius.

00:24:44.680 --> 00:24:46.132
I love technology.

00:24:46.132 --> 00:24:47.340
I've always loved technology.

00:24:47.340 --> 00:24:50.014
I've had early everything.

00:24:50.014 --> 00:24:51.430
I had one of the
first CD players.

00:24:51.430 --> 00:24:55.300
I had early everything
that's been coming out

00:24:55.300 --> 00:24:57.735
since I was growing up.

00:24:57.735 --> 00:25:00.610
I was the very end
of the Baby Boomer.

00:25:00.610 --> 00:25:03.360
I'm a '64 baby.

00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:09.840
