So part of that is that
we put out some content.

00:26:11.890 --> 00:26:13.790
Someone would think
well enough of it

00:26:13.790 --> 00:26:15.180
that they start to carry it.

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:18.790
And using analytics--
YouTube's some great analytics.

00:26:18.790 --> 00:26:20.380
Google has great analytics.

00:26:20.380 --> 00:26:22.650
We can actually
really understand

00:26:22.650 --> 00:26:27.449
who's using those
videos, who likes them.

00:26:27.449 --> 00:26:28.990
And then we can go
and cater to them.

00:26:28.990 --> 00:26:34.550
In our situation, we
communicate out to about 185

00:26:34.550 --> 00:26:39.580
different-- from the dark side
of things-- digital publishers

00:26:39.580 --> 00:26:41.890
that over time have
carried our content.

00:26:41.890 --> 00:26:43.360
And some of them do really well.

00:26:43.360 --> 00:26:46.100
Some of them are pretty
big digital publishers.

00:26:46.100 --> 00:26:48.860
Little Things, which ranks
really high right now

00:26:48.860 --> 00:26:50.224
in terms of the mobile world.

00:26:50.224 --> 00:26:56.040
The Animal Rescue Site is a
monster in terms of depth.

00:26:56.040 --> 00:26:58.470
It's part of the Greater
Good Organization, just

00:26:58.470 --> 00:27:01.224
on their Animal Rescue Site
Facebook page, like 6 million,

00:27:01.224 --> 00:27:04.330
but very active viewers.

00:27:04.330 --> 00:27:07.062
Rough Life, I think,
is one of the videos

00:27:07.062 --> 00:27:08.562
we were just recently
talking about,

00:27:08.562 --> 00:27:11.630
just passed a half-million
views in the last six weeks.

00:27:11.630 --> 00:27:14.090
And it did exceedingly well.

00:27:14.090 --> 00:27:19.250
They did 150,000 shares in
three days off of that one.

00:27:19.250 --> 00:27:20.890
But then, that's
what happens, too.

00:27:20.890 --> 00:27:25.220
In a viral sense,
we are absolutely

00:27:25.220 --> 00:27:28.690
selling some of our content
through these channels now.

00:27:28.690 --> 00:27:31.290
And how you set them
up, how you build

00:27:31.290 --> 00:27:34.252
them, the cards that you use,
the metatags that you use,

00:27:34.252 --> 00:27:35.740
the title.

00:27:35.740 --> 00:27:37.250
People will notice
that our titles,

00:27:37.250 --> 00:27:40.700
that they're longer titles, but
they're all very descriptive.

00:27:40.700 --> 00:27:43.330
"Puppy in pipe terrified."

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:45.860
So it's all these
very descriptive words

00:27:45.860 --> 00:27:48.510
that help generate and make
those other connections.

00:27:48.510 --> 00:27:51.560
And once we get to a certain
point with each of our videos

00:27:51.560 --> 00:27:53.880
that goes out to a
pipeline, gets to a point,

00:27:53.880 --> 00:27:59.612
then it starts to do a
regular wavelength of content.

00:27:59.612 --> 00:28:01.570
And I don't know if it's
how people are finding

00:28:01.570 --> 00:28:03.120
it, the tags, and so on.

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:07.670
So our video's then start to
be these little engines that

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:08.467
start to continue.

00:28:08.467 --> 00:28:10.050
But you got to get
to a certain point.

00:28:10.050 --> 00:28:13.530
And I don't know
what that is just yet

00:28:13.530 --> 00:28:14.912
when they start to just roll.

00:28:14.912 --> 00:28:17.370
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: How do you
know when you're succeeding?

00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:20.880
You have your subscriber
base is going up, more views.

00:28:20.880 --> 00:28:23.990
And what's ultimately your
goal, then, with awareness?

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:30.150
TOM MCPHEE: Our goal, really,
is to try to make it very easy,

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:33.620
like ESPN, to look
into this realm

00:28:33.620 --> 00:28:36.090
and sort through what's
real and what's not.

00:28:36.090 --> 00:28:40.230
I mean, they're first
entity that I look in.

00:28:40.230 --> 00:28:42.250
They're omnipresent,
they deal with sports.

00:28:42.250 --> 00:28:46.210
I think this is as big of
a market segment that's

00:28:46.210 --> 00:28:50.620
heavily underserved because it
hasn't been served properly.

00:28:50.620 --> 00:28:53.776
The producers in the past, or
the broadcasters in the past,

00:28:53.776 --> 00:28:56.695
they become somewhat
users of the content

00:28:56.695 --> 00:28:58.905
and then users of
the environment.

00:28:58.905 --> 00:29:00.060
We don't want to do that.

00:29:00.060 --> 00:29:03.220
We actually have
a no-touching-- we

00:29:03.220 --> 00:29:06.610
are banned from interacting
with animals whatsoever.

00:29:06.610 --> 00:29:10.200
Our objective is to
communicate all of the stories

00:29:10.200 --> 00:29:14.000
out there of all the nonprofits
that are doing righteous work.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:17.726
And there's literally
tens of thousands of them.

00:29:17.726 --> 00:29:19.790
And for us, when
we start to look

00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:22.166
at what they do, the
interactions that they

00:29:22.166 --> 00:29:24.210
have, and we start to
build stories around them,

00:29:24.210 --> 00:29:26.760
then we start to create
that impact for them.

00:29:26.760 --> 00:29:29.760
For the people that are
watching the content,

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:33.940
for us to build a base of
broadcasters and production

00:29:33.940 --> 00:29:36.890
departments that come to us
because we monetize what we're

00:29:36.890 --> 00:29:38.182
doing a lot of different ways.

00:29:38.182 --> 00:29:39.140
You talk about success.

00:29:39.140 --> 00:29:40.940
What's successful?

00:29:40.940 --> 00:29:44.420
For us, our numbers of
views are exceedingly

00:29:44.420 --> 00:29:46.020
high for our subscribers.

00:29:46.020 --> 00:29:49.660
We're going to hit about 13,000
subscribers here shortly.

00:29:49.660 --> 00:29:53.150
We're working with a
consulting company right now.

00:29:53.150 --> 00:29:57.740
And our goal is by this
time September of next year

00:29:57.740 --> 00:29:59.492
to be 100,000 subscribers.

00:29:59.492 --> 00:30:03.000
So we've got 87,000
to go in 10 months.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:04.760
So that's one way to measure it.

00:30:04.760 --> 00:30:07.070
But for us, it's also donations.

00:30:07.070 --> 00:30:09.770
Are we generating
the donations that we

00:30:09.770 --> 00:30:11.910
should through these programs?

00:30:11.910 --> 00:30:14.750
Everything that we do is
generated from outside income,

00:30:14.750 --> 00:30:18.560
whether we license
content, whether we

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:21.070
do work for hire-- so
someone might go, hey,

00:30:21.070 --> 00:30:22.760
we need this kind of
stuff-- everything

00:30:22.760 --> 00:30:26.330
then goes back into World Animal
Awareness Society and WA2S

00:30:26.330 --> 00:30:28.565
Films so we can
actually tell stories

00:30:28.565 --> 00:30:31.410
about all these other
organizations that

00:30:31.410 --> 00:30:34.240
have no communications entity.

00:30:34.240 --> 00:30:36.400
They rely on someone like us.

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:39.640
We want to be Vice, ESPN,
and National Geographic.

00:30:39.640 --> 00:30:42.690
Five years from now, when
we have this conversation,

00:30:42.690 --> 00:30:44.900
I expect it to be in one
of the YouTube auditoriums

00:30:44.900 --> 00:30:47.010
on one of the coasts.

00:30:47.010 --> 00:30:49.340
And we're greeting
so many people

00:30:49.340 --> 00:30:51.800
because we've been then
broadcasting for a year

00:30:51.800 --> 00:30:52.820
already 24/7.

00:30:52.820 --> 00:30:55.928
And we've got our mass
audience that we can tap into.

00:30:55.928 --> 00:30:57.374
So you might find [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:57.374 --> 00:30:58.707
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Yeah, great.

00:30:58.707 --> 00:30:59.912
That's exciting.

00:30:59.912 --> 00:31:01.786
Let's talk about your
lifestyle a little bit.

00:31:01.786 --> 00:31:04.864
As capturing all this film,
I imagine you're on the road

00:31:04.864 --> 00:31:05.814
quite a bit.

00:31:05.814 --> 00:31:06.480
TOM MCPHEE: Yes.

00:31:06.480 --> 00:31:08.063
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
What is that like?

00:31:08.063 --> 00:31:09.745
For people that are
used to a 9-5 job--

00:31:09.745 --> 00:31:10.370
TOM MCPHEE: No.

00:31:10.370 --> 00:31:12.369
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: --how's
that differ for you?

00:31:12.369 --> 00:31:13.510
TOM MCPHEE: Yes.

00:31:13.510 --> 00:31:14.144
Yes, it does.

00:31:14.144 --> 00:31:15.185
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Yeah.

00:31:15.185 --> 00:31:17.310
Tell us what your typical
week might look like.

00:31:17.310 --> 00:31:19.435
TOM MCPHEE: Seriously,
look, there's no such thing.

00:31:19.435 --> 00:31:23.246
I burn through houses and
wives and girlfriends.

00:31:23.246 --> 00:31:28.090
And I am very happy to say
I am in a really happy point

00:31:28.090 --> 00:31:32.170
in my life because
the love of my life

00:31:32.170 --> 00:31:35.030
happens to be also
a partner in crime

00:31:35.030 --> 00:31:37.887
and loves being on the
front lines here capturing

00:31:37.887 --> 00:31:39.350
this stuff.

00:31:39.350 --> 00:31:43.710
Yesterday, Sunday mornings are
normally like go to the movies

00:31:43.710 --> 00:31:46.090
because you got a rave.

00:31:46.090 --> 00:31:48.618
On first movie of the
day, it's like $5,

00:31:48.618 --> 00:31:50.714
real cheap for a
first-run movie.

00:31:50.714 --> 00:31:52.900
And think we wanted to
see "Bridge of Spies"

00:31:52.900 --> 00:31:57.676
and break down some of the film,
look at it, watch the movie

00:31:57.676 --> 00:32:00.150
and enjoy it, but also
look at it as filmmakers.

00:32:00.150 --> 00:32:02.250
And instead, because
it was so nice,

00:32:02.250 --> 00:32:07.525
we decided to go and film this
rescue of 13 dogs, six puppies,

00:32:07.525 --> 00:32:10.970
which is now at wa2s.org,
because we wanted

00:32:10.970 --> 00:32:13.240
to actually practice
our filmmaking skills

00:32:13.240 --> 00:32:16.490
and work with this new camera.

00:32:16.490 --> 00:32:20.932
There is no-- I have, from
what I understand, we all die.

00:32:20.932 --> 00:32:25.032
I have a limited number of
days between now and then.

00:32:25.032 --> 00:32:26.490
And I go, that's
what I want to do.

00:32:26.490 --> 00:32:28.890
And there's a lot of things
that I need to learn, especially

00:32:28.890 --> 00:32:30.766
as we roll into some
of this new technology,

00:32:30.766 --> 00:32:33.260
and we're using some
online platforms,

00:32:33.260 --> 00:32:35.220
and we're smushing
it all together.

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:41.450
So don't expect golf
trips, bass fishing.

00:32:41.450 --> 00:32:43.250
I used to do all that stuff.

00:32:43.250 --> 00:32:43.910
I used to ski.

00:32:43.910 --> 00:32:45.420
I used to go fishing
all the time.

00:32:45.420 --> 00:32:47.730
I used to play 30,
40 rounds of golf.

00:32:47.730 --> 00:32:49.970
I used to travel.

00:32:49.970 --> 00:32:53.546
My travel is into a danger zone
to film these interactions.

00:32:53.546 --> 00:32:56.430
And I couldn't imagine
doing anything else.

00:32:56.430 --> 00:32:58.065
I live for this stuff.

00:32:58.065 --> 00:32:59.440
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ:
That's great.

00:32:59.440 --> 00:33:01.390
You have definitely a
lot passion about this.

00:33:01.390 --> 00:33:01.890
I can tell.

00:33:01.890 --> 00:33:03.348
I have seen you in
some what looked

00:33:03.348 --> 00:33:06.370
like dangerous neighborhoods
in some of your videos.

00:33:06.370 --> 00:33:07.330
Are you ever scared?

00:33:07.330 --> 00:33:08.170
Do you feel like
you're in danger ever?

00:33:08.170 --> 00:33:09.419
TOM MCPHEE: Not in the moment.

00:33:09.419 --> 00:33:12.850
And a lot of times, a lot of
disturbing situations, too.

00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:15.560
And I filter every
through a lens.

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:17.844
The idea for me
is I need to focus

00:33:17.844 --> 00:33:20.510
on what I'm doing because I want
you to be able to look at this.

00:33:20.510 --> 00:33:22.880
Now, afterwards, like
"American Opera,"

00:33:22.880 --> 00:33:25.710
so we captured hundreds
of hours of stuff.

00:33:25.710 --> 00:33:31.290
We're seeing footage of police
officers shooting dogs, just

00:33:31.290 --> 00:33:33.320
really horrific stuff.

00:33:33.320 --> 00:33:37.250
And then I've got to go edit
this for a couple years.

00:33:37.250 --> 00:33:41.860
The first six months of editing
that, everything caught up

00:33:41.860 --> 00:33:42.360
to me.

00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:44.395
So you're out there,
just doing whatever.

00:33:44.395 --> 00:33:47.440
It's like all-- and then
you get into the edit suite,

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:48.171
and you get in.

00:33:48.171 --> 00:33:49.045
And then things stop.

00:33:49.045 --> 00:33:51.165
And then you start
to see everything

00:33:51.165 --> 00:33:52.890
and you're building this thing.

00:33:52.890 --> 00:33:57.180
And then everything that you're
running from and filtering

00:33:57.180 --> 00:33:58.880
through catches up.

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:01.110
And I was knocked out.

00:34:01.110 --> 00:34:03.710
I cried every day for
probably 45 minutes every day.

00:34:03.710 --> 00:34:06.720
When it first started happening,
I was really freaked out.

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:07.970
And then I just let it happen.

00:34:07.970 --> 00:34:09.560
Everyday, it was
like, OK, we do that.

00:34:09.560 --> 00:34:12.419
And it actually led
to the creative stuff

00:34:12.419 --> 00:34:15.365
that came out of it. "An
American Opera" totally

00:34:15.365 --> 00:34:20.065
would not have happened if I did
not have this total meltdown.

00:34:20.065 --> 00:34:24.633
But I figured out how to
kind of deal with that stuff

00:34:24.633 --> 00:34:26.010
and to sort through.

00:34:26.010 --> 00:34:29.605
But there is-- you
can't [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:29.605 --> 00:34:31.170
We're putting out
a lot of content.

00:34:31.170 --> 00:34:32.513
We've got very impressive goals.

00:34:32.513 --> 00:34:34.179
We have a lot of
people that are getting

00:34:34.179 --> 00:34:35.636
behind what we're doing.

00:34:35.636 --> 00:34:42.095
We're interacting with HBO and
[INAUDIBLE] Productions and Nat

00:34:42.095 --> 00:34:43.659
Geographic and all these others.

00:34:43.659 --> 00:34:47.100
And there is no--
this is what we do.

00:34:47.100 --> 00:34:48.315
MARC DE SCHWEINITZ: Right.

00:34:48.315 --> 00:34:50.239
That makes sense.

00:34:50.239 --> 00:34:56.070
So what would you be
doing if WA2S graduated?

00:34:56.070 --> 00:34:58.800
Do you have any other projects
that you want to work on?

00:34:58.800 --> 00:35:01.240
Or do you plan to stay
with this organization

00:35:01.240 --> 00:35:02.510
for the next [INAUDIBLE]?

